message.content:
A 'Calidris alpina' is a small migratory shorebird commonly known as the Dunlin.
It has a black bill that curves slightly downwards.
The Dunlin has a brownish-gray back and wings with black feather tips.
During breeding season, its underparts turn a reddish-brown color.
The legs of a Dunlin are black and relatively short, adapted for walking and running on muddy or sandy surfaces.
They can be found in coastal areas, estuaries, and tundra habitats in both the Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
Dunlins are known for their distinctive flight pattern, low and fast with quick, erratic wingbeats.
